There's only one scenario that I can image which would propel the Dow below the Russell. Boeing comprises nearly 10% of the DJIA. Boeing stock has held up remarkably well in the face of the 737 MAX troubles. If BA were to suddenly drop by 30% it would put the Dow in the same ballpark as the Russell, with regard to their gains since January 31. This would seem to be a longshot, especially given that so little time is left. So I'll leave the odds the the Russell will be the laggard at 93%.

The gap between the Dow and the Russell indices has continued to widen. While the Russell could snap back, with only 5 weeks to go for the challenge it seems unlikely to close such a wide gap (4.85%). What scenario could cause the Dow to crash that would not also affect the small cap Russell index? Or what good news could cause the Russell to melt up significantly more that the Dow? Likewise regarding the even wider gap to the NASDAQ and S&P 500.
The Russell 2000 is inherently less liquid than any of the other markets. Fed draining reserve funds causes a decrease in liquidity, which will cause bigger swings in less liquid markets.

All of the market indices are weak today because of China trade concerns. The Dow and the Russell have moved closer together. I'm going to take some of "cafebedouin's" advice and do a little hedging. I wrote about the benefits of hedging in a previous forecast/post of mine, but then failed to take my own advice. I also did not calculate the risk/reward ratio for my selections. My bad! Shortcuts lead to bad outcomes.

The crowd gives the Russell 2000 and the DJIA about equal chances of underperforming (37% and 36%). Currently the Dow is lagging the other indices. If there is a trade deal with China then the large Dow stocks could improve. If the trade war gets out of hand the smaller Russell companies could outperform. So with 80 days remaining it may come down to whether or not a trade deal gets done, and when.

(I don't think this can last and i think a lot are bubbles, but you know what Keynes said about the irrationality of markets). The DJIA is a weird one, and why it still gets followed I don't know, it does not represent market activity.

The markets tanked today, with the Russell 2000 hit especially hard (up only 0.43% since Jan 31). The small cap index is the most volatile, and one would expect it to move the fastest and furthest in either direction. That makes it a wild card, but right now it is way behind the other indices. The NASDAQ is ahead (+4.96%), followed by the S&P (+3.57%). The Dow is in the middle (+2.01%). I am splitting my bet between the Dow and the Russell.

I will update the forecast every week. I believe that daily updates are not necessary since daily movements of the market are pretty random.

- R2000 has been the worst performing of these indices for all 6-month periods since the period ending 1st Oct 2018. - I also looked at how often each of these indices was the worst-performing or within 2% of the worst-performing (to hopefully account for volatility when it is a close race) for all 6-month periods since the period ending 31st July 2018, result: DJIA: 24%, Nasdaq: 4% R2000: 59%, S&P500: 13%. So this also points to R2000, like the point above. Nevertheless I am giving Nasdaq the second highest probability, because Nasdaq and R2000 are currently the two indices performing worst when looking at a 6 month sliding window. - The ratio of current value/value at end of 31 Jan 2019 sees R2000 being the best performing though (at a ratio of 1.06), with the others very close together (DJIA 1.041, Nasdaq 1.043, S&P 1.037)

In general R2K is more insulated from larger scale economic trends due to the nature of what it indices. Due to the potential volatility of global exchange markets that we are likely to see post-March 29th, I consider this of least concern. By this same coin the S&P is more likely to feel outsized effects over the DJ. NASDAQ will likely feel some degree of pressure due to changing international laws and regulation in IT spheres but the time horizon for these changes is likely outside of the allotted window.

It all seems to boil down to whether their will be a bullish/expansionist orientation or bearish/recession orientation as they are clearly ranked by risk. I have a 65% odds of recession orientation and 35% or expansion orientation with Russell 2000 riskiest, then Nasdaq, then sp500, then Dow Jones. All are in an uptrend so can't use that to distinguish; and large cap is slightlly more overvalued compared to historical norms.

If the SP500 performs bad, the NASDAQ performs worst, so I do not expect it to be the worst in the case of a bear market. Although we are reaching the end of an economic cycle, due to the FED dovish remarks in the past month I think they may soften the rate increases and that can increase the confidence of the markets. Even if they increase the rates, it can serve as moral suasion that signals to the markets that the economy is strong and healthy.

This challenge question is to forecast the relative performance of 4 US stock market indices in a designated 6 month period (31 January 2019 to 31 July 2019). If the markets and the indices were truly random, the probability of being the worst performer would be 25% for each of the indices. But are they random? Or do historical data show patterns that we can use for forecasting this question?

DJIA will benefit from US/China deal, SnP to a lesser extent. Tech and R2K may be closer to being tapped out, esp Tech so NASDAQ would be #1 contender.

Defensive sectors outperformed cyclical ones in most regions in Q4 2018. The growth leadership evident in most markets in recent quarters reversed dramatically, led by a significant sell-off in technology. Quality factors produced strong performance across major regions over the same period. As the economy fundamentals deteriorate, I expect the trends in Q4 2018 to continue into the first half of 2019. As such, small cap may lag its large cap counterparts given the perceived higher volatility and lower quality factors.
